          <h2 class="title">Who we are</h2>
          <div class="content">We go back to 1985. Red Sector Incorporated was founded that spring in North America, initially as a Commodore 64 cracking and demo group, quickly growing a European chapter spanning Germany, the US, and beyond. RSI ran the first ever Canadian BBS for the scene, and our first Amiga demo appeared in early 1987 — featuring music by Karsten Obarski, who would go on to create the SoundTracker and give birth to the entire tracked music tradition. That same year we pioneered the first inter-group cooperation on the Amiga, a practice that would become central to scene culture.</div>
          <div class="content">Tristar had been running alongside RSI throughout the late 1980s, sharing goals, events, and people. On 29 June 1990, at the Red Sector and The Silents Summer Conference in Denmark, Flynn, Nutribrains, Beermacht and the rest of the Tristar crew joined forces with RSI to form Tristar & Red Sector Inc. — what became the longest-running cooperation in scene history.</div>
          <div class="content">Through the early 1990s we were one of the most active groups on the Amiga, producing demos, intros, and cracktros across the golden era of the scene. We also created the Red Sector Demomaker, a commercial product that let Amiga users without coding skills make their own demos — an early bridge between the underground and the general public. The scene's music culture grew alongside everything else, eventually spinning off into TRSI Recordz, our own independent record label.</div>
          <div class="content">As computing shifted, we followed — from Amiga to PC, then on to consoles, handhelds, mobile, and well beyond. We've never been precious about platform; if the hardware is interesting, we want to code on it.</div>
          <div class="content">The most extreme example of that is probably 10 Orbyte (2014): a C64 demo we transmitted to, and ran aboard, a femtosatellite in orbit — taking first place in the wild compo at Revision that year. Demoscene history in space.</div>
          <div class="content">We're still here. Members spread across the world, still releasing on C64, Amiga, and PC, still going to parties, still pushing old and new hardware past where it's supposed to go.</div>

          <div class="content">Find our full production archive on <a href="https://www.pouet.net/groups.php?which=280">Pouët.net</a>, <a href="https://demozoo.org/groups/69/">Demozoo</a>, , and <a href="https://csdb.dk/group/?id=915">CSDb</a>.</div>

