          <h2 class="title">What is the demoscene?</h2>
          <div class="content">The demoscene is an international computer art subculture born from the home computer revolution of the early 1980s. It grew out of the software cracking scene, where programmers attached short animated introductions — cracktros — to games they had cracked, using them to show off skills and claim credit. These grew increasingly elaborate, and eventually groups began releasing them as standalone works: demos.</div>
          <div class="content">A demo is a self-contained program that produces real-time audiovisual output — graphics, music, animation — using only the processing power of the target machine. No video playback, no pre-rendered frames. The challenge is the point. Fitting astonishing visuals and music into impossibly small file sizes, or coaxing effects out of decades-old hardware, is a defining ethos. Demos are released at demoparties — live competitive events where groups unveil their latest work and audiences vote on the best productions.</div>
          <div class="content">From its origins on the Commodore 64 and Amiga, the scene has expanded to cover virtually every platform imaginable. It has always been non-commercial and collaborative, driven purely by the desire to create and push limits.</div>
          <div class="content">In 2020, Finland became the first country to add the demoscene to its national UNESCO list of intangible cultural heritage — the first digital subculture anywhere to receive that recognition. By 2025, seven countries had followed: Finland, Germany, Poland, Switzerland, the Netherlands, Sweden, and France. It is, in the fullest sense, a living tradition.</div>
